# Architecture

## Local-first spine

Treat the machine as the dojo. Default placement for identity, résumé, preferences, queue, timeline, and model context: **on device**.

```
✅ GOOD: local store → local LLM → queue → user approves → outbound send
❌ BAD:  auto-upload résumé → cloud LLM → auto-apply without review
```

## Outbound boundary

Anything that leaves the device (apply, email, board submit) is an **explicit boundary**:

- Require clear user intent (and approval when preferences say so).
- Record what left vs what stayed in local timeline/logs.
- Never imply success if send completion is unknown.

## Module boundaries

Respect core modules in `docs/product/FEATURES.md`: Identity & Resume, Preferences, Local Intelligence, Agent, Discovery, Applications, Queue & Review, Send, Follow-ups, Timeline, Privacy chrome.

- Keep **Agent** preparative; keep **Send** sovereign.
- **Local Intelligence** must not quietly fall back to cloud without an obvious, user-chosen path.
- **Privacy & Trust Chrome** (e.g. Local LLM badge) is part of the architecture, not optional polish.

## Desktop OS, not SaaS cockpit

- Prefer native, light, fast desktop patterns over dashboard sprawl.
- One job per view; surface progress calmly (queue, follow-ups) — no spaceship control panels.
- Dark mode first (Midnight Ink + Electric Teal); see `docs/brand/BRAND_GUIDELINES.md`.

## Extensibility

Future skills/plugins are user-enabled and inspectable. No hidden employer-side ranking or candidate surveillance features (`docs/product/NON_GOALS.md`).
